      'Systematic code review for correctness, architecture, security, and quality. Catches bugs before merge.',
    content:
      "# Code Review Checklist\n\n## Core Principle\n\nEvery merge should improve the codebase. A code review is a conversation, not a gate.\n\n## When to Use\n\n- Before approving any pull request\n- During team code review ceremonies\n- Self-review before pushing (catches 80% of issues)\n- Refactoring PRs (highest rigor)\n\n## Pre-Review Setup\n\n1. **Understand the change** — read the PR title and description\n2. **Check the scope** — is it as small as claimed?\n3. **Run the code** — build, test, manual verification\n4. **Review in order** — files that matter most first\n\n## Correctness Checklist\n\n- [ ] **Logic is correct** — trace the code path; does it match the requirement?\n- [ ] **Edge cases handled** — what if input is empty, null, NaN, negative, very large?\n- [ ] **Error handling present** — exceptions caught, not silently swallowed?\n- [ ] **Off-by-one errors** — list indices, loop bounds, pagination `limit`/`offset`?\n- [ ] **Type safety** — no `any`, casts justified with comments?\n- [ ] **Mutation bugs** — arrays/objects modified when they shouldn't be?\n- [ ] **Race conditions** — concurrent operations safe? Locks in place?\n- [ ] **State consistency** — if multiple fields updated, are they consistent after?\n\n## Architecture & Design\n\n- [ ] **Follows patterns** — reuses existing patterns or introduces better ones?\n- [ ] **Single responsibility** — function/class does one thing?\n- [ ] **Cohesion high** — related code grouped, separated from unrelated?\n- [ ] **Coupling loose** — dependencies flow one direction, no cycles?\n- [ ] **Testability** — easy to unit test in isolation?\n- [ ] **Naming clear** — variable/function names say what they do?\n- [ ] **Complexity reasonable** — not a 200-line function doing 5 things?\n- [ ] **DRY respected** — code repeated 3+ times gets extracted?\n\n## Code Quality\n\n- [ ] **No dead code** — unused variables, imports, commented-out lines removed?\n- [ ] **No debugging artifacts** — `console.log`, `debugger`, `//TODO` commented out?\n- [ ] **Consistent with project** — style, naming, patterns match the codebase?\n- [ ] **Comments explain why, not what** — code says what, comments say why\n- [ ] **String handling** — hardcoded strings extracted to i18n or constants?\n- [ ] **Magic numbers gone** — `60000` → `TIMEOUT_MS` constant?\n- [ ] **Formatting clean** — linter passes, no style fights?\n\n## Security & Safety\n\n- [ ] **No secrets committed** — API keys, tokens, passwords in .env not code?\n- [ ] **Injection prevented** — user input parameterized before DB/template?\n- [ ] **Auth checked** — protected endpoints verify user before proceeding?\n- [ ] **Data validation** — all external input (API, form, file) validated?\n- [ ] **Dependencies safe** — no known CVEs? (`npm audit`, `pip audit`)\n- [ ] **Cryptography correct** — not custom crypto, using stdlib?\n- [ ] **Sensitive logs redacted** — tokens/credentials never logged in plaintext?\n- [ ] **CORS configured** — if using CORS, whitelist specific origins not `*`?\n\n## Testing\n\n- [ ] **Tests written first** — test failures included in PR?\n- [ ] **Coverage adequate** — happy path + error cases + edge cases tested?\n- [ ] **Tests independent** — test A doesn't affect test B?\n- [ ] **Mocks reasonable** — mocks match real behavior closely?\n- [ ] **No flaky tests** — tests pass consistently, no timing issues?\n- [ ] **Test names descriptive** — name says what behavior is being tested?\n\n## Performance\n\n- [ ] **No obvious inefficiencies** — nested loops doing unnecessary work?\n- [ ] **Queries optimized** — N+1 query patterns avoided?\n- [ ] **Large objects avoided** — megabyte payloads serialized unnecessarily?\n- [ ] **Caching considered** — expensive operations cached when safe?\n- [ ] **Async where needed** — blocking I/O on event loop? Use async/await or workers?\n\n## When to Request Changes\n\n**MUST FIX (blocks merge):**\n- Correctness bugs or logic errors\n- Security vulnerabilities\n- Test failures\n- Architecture violations\n\n**SHOULD FIX (discuss with author):**\n- Missing test coverage\n- Dead code\n- Unclear naming\n- Style inconsistency\n- Performance concerns\n\n**NICE TO HAVE (optional):**\n- Refactoring suggestions (if PR not focused on refactoring)\n- Nitpicks on comments\n\n## Approval Criteria\n\nApprove when:\n\n1. Correctness is solid (logic matches requirement, no bugs found)\n2. Tests adequate (good coverage, independent tests)\n3. Code quality acceptable (readable, maintainable, follows project patterns)\n4. Security acceptable (no vulnerabilities, secrets safe)\n5. Architecture sound (fits codebase, no regressions)\n\nApprove even if not perfect — perfect is the enemy of done.\n\n## Remember\n\n```\nCorrectness first\nThen architecture\nThen quality\nThen nice-to-haves\n\nRequest changes only on issues that matter\nApprove good-enough\nLearn from reviews\n```",
